y, sociology, and economics from Canada, the United States, England, Germany, and Australia advance not only the most recent theories of how modern societies are governed, but also the ideological and political relevance of these theories. The focus of this collection is on the extent to which the nature and practice of governance has dramatically changed. The realities of cutbacks in social security expenditures, changes in technology, shifts in labour markets, politics of identity and group rights, loss of political autonomy by nation-states, and management by surveillance and audit all underscore the evolution of governing. The fact that such shifts are also connected to new forms of governance beyond the state (at the community level, for example, within corporate institutions and through the influence of social movements and economic markets) makes the task of governing modern societies all the more challenging.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAtkinson, Anthony B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeiner, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroadbent, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElkins, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEricson, Richard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeld, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHindess, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagnusson, Warren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOffe, Claus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Nikolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov